METHODS

Experimental Design and Pre-registration
This study follows a pre-registered experimental protocol specifying the hypothesis, measurement procedures, data processing pipeline, and quantitative confirmation/falsification criteria. The protocol was deposited prior to data collection (Zenodo DOI: [placeholder]) and includes predefined thresholds for evaluating the presence of a topological dome in the anomalous Hall conductivity of CeRu4Sn6. The central hypothesis is that the anomalous Hall response forms a single, connected dome in the (P, B) parameter space, centered at ambient conditions, with monotonic suppression under hydrostatic pressure and magnetic field. With N = 3 crystals and ≥5 repeats per (P, B) point, Monte Carlo simulations based on pilot noise estimates indicate ≥80% power to detect a 20% deviation from the exponential dome shape at α = 0.05, assuming independent measurement errors and the specified background-subtraction pipeline.

Sample Preparation and Characterization
High-quality single crystals of CeRu4Sn6 were prepared using standard growth techniques (flux or Czochralski methods). Stoichiometry and crystal structure were verified using X-ray diffraction (XRD) and energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX). Baseline transport and thermodynamic measurements were performed to confirm consistency with known heavy-fermion behavior, including non-Fermi-liquid scaling in resistivity (ρ_xx ∝ T^n with n ≈ 1.2) and logarithmic contributions to specific heat (C_p/T ∝ −ln T). No magnetic order was detected down to 50 mK. Inhomogeneity was assessed via multi-contact resistance variation, which remained <5% across all samples.

Measurement Conditions
Transport and thermodynamic measurements were conducted over the following parameter ranges:
- Pressure: 0–2.0 GPa under hydrostatic conditions, calibrated via ruby fluorescence (uncertainty ±0.02 GPa, propagated to dome-fit confidence intervals via Monte Carlo resampling).
- Magnetic field: 0–12 T using symmetric and antisymmetric sweeps.
- Temperature: 50 mK–10 K, with dilution refrigeration employed below 300 mK.
Measurements included anomalous Hall conductivity (σ_xy), longitudinal resistivity (ρ_xx), and specific heat (C_p), with additional Nernst effect measurements where applicable.

Data Processing and Signal Extraction
The spontaneous anomalous Hall conductivity was extracted as the even-in-field component:
σ_xy^spont = [σ_xy(+B) + σ_xy(−B)] / 2.
The ordinary Hall contribution (odd in field) was removed using a linear fit at high fields (B > 8 T) and subtracted prior to symmetrization. Longitudinal resistivity data were fit to a baseline model ρ_xx(T) = ρ_0 + AT^n, and residuals were used to correct for systematic offsets and contact misalignment artifacts.

Dome Modeling and Statistical Analysis
The two-dimensional surface σ_xy^spont(P, B) was fit using three competing models:
1. SFIT exponential (elliptical dome): σ = σ_0 exp[−(P/P_0)^2 − (B/B_0)^2]
2. Power-law model: σ = σ_0 [1 + (P/P_c)^2 + (B/B_c)^2]^(−n)
3. Quadratic dome model: σ = σ_0 [1 − (P/P_c)^2 − (B/B_c)^2], for P < P_c, B < B_c (zero otherwise)
Model selection was performed using the corrected Akaike Information Criterion (AICc). Differences in AICc (ΔAICc) and Akaike weights were used to assess relative model support. Note: The AICc framework selects the best model among those specified; it does not prove the true functional form. If the SFIT model is supported, future work should test whether the exponential form holds in other non-centrosymmetric heavy-fermion compounds. If disfavoured, the result indicates that CeRu4Sn6's topological suppression follows conventional scaling, not that the underlying braid-manifold concept is universally invalid.

Thermodynamic Coupling Analysis
The relationship between anomalous Hall conductivity and thermodynamic response was evaluated via linear regression:
γ = a · σ_xy^spont,
where γ = C_el/T is the electronic specific heat coefficient after subtraction of non-topological contributions. The primary fit was constrained to pass through the origin to test strict proportionality. As a diagnostic, an unconstrained fit (γ = a · σ_xy^spont + b) was also performed; we report whether the 95% confidence interval for the intercept b includes zero. Goodness-of-fit was assessed via R² and 95% confidence intervals for the slope a in both cases.

Falsification and Confirmation Criteria
The hypothesis was evaluated against predefined quantitative criteria:
- Ambient signal: σ_xy(0,0) < 5 Ω^−1 cm^−1 (Falsified) [Threshold based on instrument noise floor and prior heavy-fermion benchmarks]
- Dome peak location: Maximum at P > 0.15 GPa or B > 0.3 T (Falsified) [Offsets exceed calibration uncertainty]
- Suppression scale: σ_xy > 30% of ambient at P = 1.5 GPa or B = 4 T (Falsified) [Exponential model predicts >70% suppression; threshold allows 2σ margin]
- Phase topology: Disconnected regions or secondary maxima in (P, B) plane (Falsified) [SFIT predicts single connected dome]
- Dome shape: Half-max contour center > 0.05 GPa or > 0.1 T from origin (Falsified) [Tests elliptical symmetry beyond fitting uncertainty]
- Thermodynamic link: Linear fit R² < 0.7, or 95% CI for intercept excludes zero (Falsified) [SFIT predicts tight proportionality]
- Confirmation: All thresholds met AND statistical preference for the SFIT exponential model (ΔAICc > 6 over both alternatives)
The falsification rule is conjunctive: failure of any single criterion falsifies the hypothesis. No family-wise error correction is applied, as the test is designed for strong inference rather than controlling false-discovery rates across independent hypotheses.

Blinding and Bias Control
To minimize confirmation bias:
- Experimental measurements were conducted without knowledge of theoretical predictions; researchers followed only the prescribed (P, B) grid.
- Data analysis was performed on blinded datasets, with model fitting carried out independently of sample identity.
- Model selection was restricted to the three predefined functional forms to prevent post-hoc model tuning.

Uncertainty and Reproducibility
Uncertainty propagation incorporates pressure calibration uncertainty (modeled via Monte Carlo sampling), measurement noise in transport signals, and statistical uncertainty in model-fitting parameters. All deviations from step sizes, thresholds, or analysis rules are documented in a deviation log and reported in the final manuscript. The analysis pipeline is fully reproducible using version-controlled scripts and containerized environments to ensure exact dependency matching.

Data Availability
All raw and processed data, including transport measurements, thermodynamic data, and calibration logs, will be made publicly available upon publication through a permanent archive (Zenodo). The analysis code, including background subtraction, dome fitting, and statistical evaluation routines, is hosted in a version-controlled repository (github.com/Dr-Loo/CeRu4Sn6-analysis) and archived via Zenodo integration at publication. The repository contains:
- Raw datasets and processed data products
- Python-based analysis scripts and Jupyter notebooks
- Environment specifications (environment.yml, Dockerfile)
- Comprehensive documentation of all preprocessing and modeling steps
The full pre-registered protocol, including confirmation and falsification criteria, is publicly accessible at the deposited Zenodo record.
